At last week's meeting of Ministers of the European space Agency Poland was adopted by the twentieth member of the European space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA September 12, 2008).
Poland began collaboration with ESA in 1994, and during the subsequent years, took an active part in a number of projects of the Agency.
But the way to outer space Poland began much earlier.
Even before the Second world war, Polish enthusiasts were flights into space, but this is not always met with understanding.
Let me remind you, for example, about the lecture And. Штернфельда, which on December 6, 1933 represented in the astronomical Observatory of the ideas from his pioneering work "Introduction to engineering".
The idea of a young engineer (born in 1905.) leave the audience indifferent, after several years of Штернфельд recalled that only Dr. Ian Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934 in France Штернфельд won the Robert Esnault-Пельтри and Andre Louis Hirsch for the "Introduction to engineering".
Dr. Ian Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), which was mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published in Polish magazines hundreds of articles and wrote a series of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became known world promoter of space, and its contribution was estimated at including the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925 in Poland was built railway trolley, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remains unknown, as well as details of the project.
It is not clear even to disperse or to stop the trolley was to be used rocket.
Information about this the cart is known only from the press of the time.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to think about the missile arrows.
A study conducted Section technology weapons in collaboration with professors Mieczys? Вольфке and Gustav Мокжицким.
Of the remaining materials shows that the research progressed to the stage of practical tests.
But with the arrival of the German troops work was interrupted.
In 1937 in specialized print the idea of the photovoltaic missile destroyer, which was proposed by the engineer Rogosinski, and in the following year came the work of "Air missile-torpedo, and aviation rocket-bomb" of the author Леливы-Кживоблоцкого.
Both projects were developed for military use of rocket engines.
Before the war all of the projects of the military use of missile technology was engaged in the Interim scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), who coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of its activity the end of the outbreak of the war.
The following scientific work devoted to the cosmonautics, appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time about the company mentioned in the November issue of 1954 of the journal "Problems", which contains four large article on Astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Суботович proposed to organize a society, which will be engaged in space science and technology.
At that time already gaining momentum projects of artificial satellites, and it was clear that the space research is a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish society of Astronautics (PHA) tried to join the international Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951), and already in the autumn, it became its full member.
And in the following year, the first Chairman of the PHA Kazimierz Заранкевич (1902 - 1959) was the Vice President of the International Federation of Astronautics.
In this position he remained until his death, which occurred in 1959.
Since 1956, has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful meteorological rockets RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish missile, made a scientific study.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The missile, capable to overcome a distance of 1800 m, was in the length of about 80 cm, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later there was built the advanced version of RM-1A, and in the summer of 1959 on the Бледовском wasteland, tests were carried out a two-stage missile RM-2.
The missile was in the length of about 1.4 m, and its weight was approximately 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already able to do real scientific work " rocket RM-34 could overcome 14,5 km, and its task was watching high-altitude wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor of the first missiles of the RM became rocket meteor-1, developed in the period between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and a starting weight of 32.5 kg.
Were developed three types (identified as meteor-1A, -1B and 1C), which varied the size of the camera for the scientific equipment.
Rocket meteor-1A had the space of a volume of 0.4 l, meteor-1B - 0,34 l, and meteor-1C - 0,62л.
Maximum flight range with all three types is 37 km.
In the period between 1965 and 1968 in the Aviation Institute was the development of rocket meteor-2 and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
Rocket meteor-2 with a starting weight of 380 kg was able to bring the payload weight of 10 kg at a height of about 60 km.
Then were built version of meteor-2 and meteor-3.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to COSPAR (Committee on space research) in 1960, and the establishment of the national Committee of COSPAR two years later.
In addition, in the framework of the program Intercosmos, Poland participated in the research of outer space for the Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Germashevsky became the second интеркосмонавтом after Vladimir Ремека.
