Signs pointed to the two queues: one for Mexicanos (Mexican), the second is for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I a few seconds, stood in front of them, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in Central California, and my whole life was called a Mexican.
It's just the code name, just as my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends from new York consider themselves Italians.
Later I stopped at a complex structure, "an American of Mexican origin".
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in the homeland of my grandfather, there was no need in conventional names or complex designs.
I was just American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of the bearers of the language, and I can't get rid of the American accent.
Because I got my American passport, and stood in a queue for Extranjeros.
